english:
  title: Reply to the Previous Letter
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: "I bow respectfully and offer this letter from afar to Master Kwon of the Northern Plain.\n\nRecently I received your reply to Yi Dam-ji, and together with it, a poem you graciously sent to me. Upon reading it with reverent attention, my heart swelled with gratitude and contrition. As I turned over each word, it was as though I stood in your presence, listening to your sage discourse.\n\nIn my youth, I heard from elder scholars that you are among the great minds of our age, and that those fortunate enough to study under you are invariably persons of distinction. I too have harbored profound admiration, yet having never received your personal attention, I have long carried this as a regret. Moreover, my uncle of Mi-ju rose to prominence through the patronage of the late Scholar, and thus our families have long shared ties of mutual obligation. I have wished many times to approach your discourse with the reverence of a student, yet my shoulders have long fallen short of touching the boundary of your wisdom.\n\nLast winter, I happened to meet with a Buddhist monk called Jung-eun in the capital, and learned much of your affairs. When he spoke of your unchanging attachment to the ideals of Ki-san and Yeong-su, I found myself lamenting and yearning alongside him, even to the point of tears. Then I knew truly that you are among men as a dragon is among creatures. When he departed, I sent along a humble poem, a small token of my sincerity.\n\nNow I have received your gracious reply, and the words of praise you offer are far beyond what I deserve. Yet they reveal the deep and genuine care with which a person of noble character extends kindness to the younger generation. \n\nWhen I observe those of former times who lived in straitened circumstances and withdrew from the world, I see that they often vented their frustration and indignation through their writings, leaving many words of resentment and criticism. But the poems and prose you have sent me are all harmonious and expansive, truly the words of one who has attained understanding. Your utterances are indistinguishable from those of a sage who has grasped the Way. This confirms what I have come to know—that you entrust yourself to principle and abide by your proper station, unmoved by fortune or misfortune, advancement or retreat, regarding worldly honors and profits as nothing. Is this not what is meant by withdrawing from the world without regret?\n\nNow, thoughtful people say that the peace or peril of our age depends upon whether you step forward or remain withdrawn. Yet you firmly resolve to maintain your humble station and preserve your noble integrity, dwelling in mountain solitude to enjoy untroubled repose. Should you do so, there would be no one left to shepherd the affairs of the realm. Yet in ancient times, Shin Mil observed that those who escape calamity do not do so by fleeing, but rather because their quiet minds naturally align with fortune. Thus we understand that the wise man serves equally well in the court or in the mountains—both are the same. This is the subtle principle of exhausting the nature of things, and who but you could embody and practice it?\n\nI earnestly entreat you: reflect deeply, and should you heed the voice of the world and rise to answer the sovereign's call, you would bring blessing to all the people under heaven. If our Way were to flourish greatly, all things would benefit from it. Even one withered and forgotten like myself might receive some overflow of that grace. How could I not be numbered among all things? This is what brings greatest joy to my heart.\n\nRecently I have heard that you keep your gates closed, teaching your disciples daily, and the sound of their recitation grows ever louder, rivaling the schools of the ancient sages by the Shu and Si rivers. This is not something enjoyed only by hermits who shun the world. For wherever a person of true cultivation dwells, others receive his gifts—this requires no official rank or title. I urge you most earnestly to persevere in this.\n\nI expect to return to my native place before summer's beginning, and I look forward then to visiting you and personally asking about the Way. The distant frontier has its own seasons of cold and heat. I humbly request that you nourish yourself well, preserve your health, and maintain harmony with heaven, so that my simple wishes might be fulfilled.\n\nWith utmost respect, I remain your devoted servant."
  footnotes:
    - 'Ki-san and Yeong-su: References to the hermit ideals of ancient China, representing a life of virtue lived in withdrawal from worldly affairs.'
    - 'Shu and Si rivers: References to the ancient centers of sage learning, particularly associated with Confucius and his followers.'
    - 'The letter wrestles with a central tension in Korean Neo-Confucian thought: whether a virtuous person should serve in government or retreat to pursue learning—arguing that true virtue transcends this distinction.'
